body:
The assignment suggestion by @Carreau doesn't appear to work unfortunately. As far as editing `custom.js` goes, these two methods work:

``` javascript
// This DOES work
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys = {'Home': 'goLineLeft',
                                                    'End': 'goLineRight'};

// This DOES work
$([IPython.events]).on('app_initialized.NotebookApp', function() {
    IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys = {'Home': 'goLineLeft',
                                                        'End': 'goLineRight'};
});
```

but none of these do:

``` javascript
// This does NOT work - keys still bound to goLineStartSmart/goLineEnd
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys[Home] = 'goLineLeft';
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys[End] = 'goLineRight';

// This does NOT work - keys still bound to goLineStartSmart/goLineEnd
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['Home'] = 'goLineLeft';
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['End'] = 'goLineRight';

// This does NOT work - keys still bound to goLineStartSmart/goLineEnd
//     Might be wrong object to access addKeyMap on
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.addKeyMap( {'Home': 'goLineLeft',
                                                   'End': 'goLineRight'} );

// This does NOT work - keys still bound to goLineStartSmart/goLineEnd
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys.Key('Home') = 'goLineLeft';
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys.Key('End') = 'goLineRight';

// This does NOT work - keys still bound to goLineStartSmart/goLineEnd
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.keyMap['Home'] = 'goLineLeft';
IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.keyMap['End'] = 'goLineRight';


// This does NOT work - notebook hangs, never finishes loading
$([IPython.events]).on('app_initialized.NotebookApp', function() {
    IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['Home'] = 'goLineLeft';
    IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['End'] = 'goLineRight';
});

// This does NOT work - notebook hangs, never finishes loading
$([IPython.events]).on('app_initialized.NotebookApp', function() {
    IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys.Key('Home') = 'goLineLeft';
    IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys.Key('End') = 'goLineRight';
});

// This does NOT work - notebook hangs, never finishes loading
//     Might be wrong object to access addKeyMap on
$([IPython.events]).on('app_initialized.NotebookApp', function() {
    IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.addKeyMap( {'Home': 'goLineLeft',
                                                       'End': 'goLineRight'} );
});
```

```
require(["base/js/events"], function (events) {
    events.on('app_initialized.NotebookApp', function() {
        IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['Home'] = 'goLineUp';
        IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['End' ] = 'goLineRight';
    });
})
```

Notebook hang because `$` is undefined on master (race condition) you need to wrap it in a require call to get it. But in the end if you use requre you do not need jquery, you can "just" rely on the even object.

If you want a more 'dict like' approach you can make use of jquery [`.extend()`](http://api.jquery.com/jquery.extend/) to extend  `IPython.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys`

Cleaner, require the cell module and patch `cell.Cell` instead of accessing the IPython global : 

```
require(["base/js/events","notebook/js/cell"], function (events,cell) {
    events.on('app_initialized.NotebookApp', function() {
        cell.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['Home'] = 'goLineUp';
        cell.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['End' ] = 'goLineRight';
        console.log('MonkeyPatchin CM cell keymat to :',cell.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys)
    });
})
```

and looking at this, you see that you do not even need `events` module to patch as the right time as now you are sure the module exist. And as `main.js` requires custom, you can limit yourself to : 

```
require(["notebook/js/cell"], function (cell) { // read as import notebook.js.cell as cell
    cell.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['Home'] = 'goLineUp';
    cell.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys['End' ] = 'goLineRight';
    console.log('MonkeyPatchin CM cell keymat to :',cell.Cell.options_default.cm_config.extraKeys)
})
```

Does it makes sens ?

Yes that explanation makes sense. I won't have a chance to try this until probably Monday, though. 

